<TITLE> PM in New Delhi </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Sumon Mahbub bdnews24.com correspondent New Delhi, Jan 10 (bdnews24.com)--Prime minister Sheikh Hasina arrived in New Delhi on Sunday to a red carpet welcome on her maiden state visit to neighbouring India after her party formed government one year back. India's state minister external affairs Preeneet Kaur received Hasina when a special flight of Biman Bangladesh Airlines touched down at Palam Air Force Base outside Delhi at 8.05pm local time. Bangladesh high commissioner in India Tariq A Karim was also present there. She was then driven to the Maurya Sheraton Hotel & Towers situated in the Indian capital's Diplomatic Enclave, the usual place of stay for visiting heads of state and government. Her schedule for Sunday night is 'quiet time'. Over the following three days, the prime minister will meet Indian president Pratibha Patil, ruling Congress party chief Sonia Gandhi and leader of the opposition Sushma Swaraj op top of the crucial summit with prime minister Manmohan Singh. Foreign minister Dipu Moni, water resources minister Romesh Chandra Sen, prime minister's advisers HT Imam, Moshiur Rahman and Gowhor Rizvi, her principal secretary Abdul Karim and foreign secretary M Mizarul Quayes are among the delegation. Her family are also accompanying the prime minister. Three treaties on crime control and a memorandum of understanding on power are supposed to be signed during the tour. Talks on other key areas including trade, infrastructure projects and sharing of river waters will also feature prominently. The official talks with Singh and signing of the agreements and MoU will take place on Monday at Hyderabad House. Hasina will attend a banquet hosted by Singh later in the evening. A large business delegation from Bangladesh is also accompanying the prime minister, who will address functions organised by the Confederation of Indian Industries (CII), the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FICCI) and Association of Chambers. Hasina will offer prayers at the grave of Sufu saint Khwaja Moinuddin Chishti at Ajmer and pay homage at the mausoleum of Mahatma Gandhi at Rajghat. She will also be conferred the prestigious Indira Gandhi Prize for Peace, Disarmament and Development in New Delhi. An international jury, chaired by Indian prime minister Manmohan Singh, chose Hasina for her "outstanding contribution to the promotion of democracy and pluralism," the Indira Gandhi Memorial Trust said announcing her as the 2009 recipient of the prize. Introduced in 1986, the award in past years has been given to, among others, former UN chief Kofi Annan, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, former Soviet Union president Mikhail Gorbachev, IAEA chief Mohammad Al Baradei, Nobel Peace prize laureates Dr Muhammad Younus and Wangari Maathai and Afghan president Hamid Karzai. bdnew
